{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Ennio De Giorgi | image = Ennio de Giorgi.jpg | image_size = 190px | caption = | birth_date={{birth date|df=y|1928|2|8}} | birth_place =[[Lecce]], [[Italy]] | death_date ={{death date and age|df=y|1996|10|25|1928|2|8}} | death_place =[[Pisa]], [[Italy]] | residence = | nationality = Italian | field =[[Calculus of variations]], [[Partial differential equation]]s | work_institution =[[Scuola Normale Superiore di Pisa]] | alma_mater =[[Sapienza University of Rome]] | doctoral_advisor =[[Mauro Picone]] | doctoral_students ={{plainlist| *[[Luigi Ambrosio]] *[[Andrea Braides|Andréa Braides]] *[[Gianni Dal Maso]]}} | known_for = [[Caccioppoli set|theory of Caccioppoli sets]], [[Hilbert's nineteenth problem|solution of 19th Hilbert problem]], [[Minimal surface|existence and regularity theorem for minimal surfaces]] | prizes = {{plainlist| *[[Caccioppoli Prize]] (1960) *[[Wolf Prize]] (1990)}} | religion = Catholic | footnotes =}}
'''Ennio De Giorgi''' (8 February 1928 – 25 October 1996) was an Italian mathematician, member of the [[House of Giorgi]], who worked on [[partial differential equation]]s and the [[foundations of mathematics]].
==Mathematical work== He solved [[Bernstein's problem]] about [[minimal surface]]s.
He solved the [[Hilbert's nineteenth problem|19th Hilbert problem]] on the regularity of solutions of [[elliptic partial differential equation]]s.
==Quotes== * "If you can't prove your theorem, keep shifting parts of the conclusion to the assumptions, until you can" <ref>Piero D'Ancona (mathoverflow.net/users/7294), Should one attack hard problems?, http://mathoverflow.net/questions/124210 (version: 2013-03-11)</ref>
